@node "MUI" "MUI"

                          @{b}MUI - MagicUserInterface@{ub}

                   (c) Copyright 1993/94 by Stefan Stuntz


 MUI  is  a system to generate and maintain graphical user interfaces.  With
 the  aid  of  a  preferences  program,  the  user of an application has the
 ability to customize the outfit according to his personal taste.

 MUI  is  distributed as shareware.  To obtain a complete package containing
 lots  of examples and more information about registration please look for a
 file  called  "muiXXusr.lha"  (XX  means the latest version number) on your
 local bulletin boards or on public domain disks.

             If you want to register directly, feel free to send


                            DM 30.-  or  US$ 20.-

                                     to

                                Stefan Stuntz
                          Eduard-Spranger-Straße 7
                                80935 München
                                   GERMANY
@endnode

@node "Inst" "Installation"

 @{b}INSTALLATION USING THE COMMODORE-INSTALLER@{ub}

 Open the directory @{b}Install@{ub}, double click on the icon @{b}English@{ub} and follow
 the instructions of the Installer.

 Please restart your Amiga after the installation if you are  updating
 from an older version of YAM.


 @{b}MANUAL INSTALLATION@{ub}

 If you don't own the Installer from AmiTech or if you don't want to use
 it, follow these instructions:

 - Create a directory for YAM on the hard disk. A good place is for example
   the directory AmiTCP.
 - Copy the files @{b}YAM@{ub}, @{b}YAM_english.guide@{ub} and the directories @{b}Icons@{ub} and
   @{b}Rexx@{ub} in this directory. Rename the guide to @{b}YAM.guide@{ub}.
 - Copy the MUI libaries @{b}listtree.mcc@{ub} and @{b}listtree.mcp@{ub} to
   @{b}MUI:libs/MUI@{ub}.
 - Copy the file @{b}textfield.gadget@{ub} to @{b}SYS:Classes/gadgets@{ub}.
 - Create an assignment YAM: to your YAM-directory in @{b}s:user-startup@{ub},
   e.g. @{b}Assign YAM: Work:AmiTCP/YAM@{ub}.
 - Reboot your computer.
@endnode

@node "Quic" "Quick Introduction"

 @{b}QUICK INTRODUCTION@{ub}

 This chapter gives you a step by step introduction of the principal
 operation of YAM. We assume that YAM is already @{"installed" link "Inst"} on your system.

 1. Get the following information from your internet provider:
    - Your email address
    - The internet address of your mail server (also called POP3- or SMTP-
      server)
    - The password to log into the mail server
    As an example we create a "fictitious" user named Bill Clinton. His
    email address is @{b}clinton@whitehouse.gov@{ub}, the address of his mail server
    is @{b}mail.whitehouse.gov@{ub} and his password is @{b}tnediserP@{ub} :-)

 2. Start YAM with double click on its icon. After a while, you should see
    the main window including four message boxes and three rows of buttons.

 3. First we must configure the program. Select the item @{b}Configuration@{ub} in
    the menu @{b}Settings@{ub}. In the register card @{b}Start@{ub} enter the required
    parameters for the mail transfer. In our example this are:

          Real name      @{b}Bill Clinton@{ub}
          POP3-Server    @{b}mail.whitehouse.gov@{ub}
          Email address  @{b}clinton@whitehouse.gov@{ub}
          Password       @{b}tnediserP@{ub}

 4. YAM allows you to add a free definable text to all your letters. Change
    to the register card @{b}Write@{ub} and select the option @{b}Use signature@{ub}.
    Start the editor with a click on @{b}[Edit signature]@{ub} and enter the
    desired signature, e.g.

    @{b}Yours sincerly,
      Billy@{ub}

    Save the text and quit the editor (for ED this works with @{b}Esc x Return@{ub}).

 5. Save the settings with a click on @{b}[Save]@{ub}. YAM is now ready and you
    are able to write your first message.

 6. Click on @{b}[Write]@{ub}. In the newly opened window select the string-gadget
    labelled @{b}To@{ub} and enter the recipient's email-address, in our example
    this is @{b}clinton@whitehouse.gov@{ub}.
    In the string-gadget @{b}Subject@{ub} you should specify the topic of your
    letter in a few words. Now click in the large empty area and enter your
    message.

 7. Since either AmiTCP isn't up yet or you're not yet connected, click on
    @{b}[To queue]@{ub}. This saves the new message in the folder "Outgoing" and
    refrains from immediate sending in contrary to @{b}[Send]@{ub}.

 8. Now start AmiTCP and build up a connection to your Internet provider.
    Change to the folder "Outgoing" and send your mail with a click on
    @{b}[Send all]@{ub}.
    In the small transfer window you may watch how YAM logs in and sends
    the mail to the mail server.

 9. As you may have noticed your message has disappeared from the folder
    "Outgoing". But don't panic; it just moved to the folder "Sent". The
    envelope in the list now has a postage stamp which means the message
    was successfully sent.

 10.Double clicking on the message opens the read window. You should
    recognize your own text. The white lines were created by YAM and contain
    necessary information for the mail transfer.

 11.Since you wrote this message to yourself, it's now time to look out for
    new messages sent to you. Click the read window into the background or
    close it and click on @{b}[Get mail]@{ub}.

 12.The now familiar transfer window appears and you can observe how YAM
    gets your mail from the mail server. If all goes well a requester opens
    up with the notice that new mail has arrived. You will find the new
    mail in the folder "Incoming".

 If you made it so far without difficulties you know now the essential
 functions of YAM. You'll find further explanations in the following
 chapters.
@endnode

@node "NdMA" "Folders"

 @{b}@{i}FOLDERS@{ui}@{ub}

 In the main window of YAM you can see four folders:

 @{b}Incoming:@{ub} This box contains all mail addressed to you.

 @{b}Outgoing:@{ub} This box contains all mail which you wrote, but hasn't been sent.

 @{b}Sent    :@{ub} This box contains all successfully sent mail.

 @{b}Archive :@{ub} This box is for archiving mail which is important for you.

 On the right side below the Archive folder list you can find a pop-up
 gadget which lets you select one of the user defined archive folders.

 The list shows the mail in the active folders. In the first column you see
 the status of the message:

 @{b}New mail@{ub}                   closed envelope from back with the letter N
 @{b}Unread mail@{ub}                closed envelope from back
 @{b}Read mail@{ub}                  opened envelope
 @{b}Replied mail@{ub}               opened envelope with the letter R
 @{b}Forwarded mail@{ub}             opened envelope with the letter F
 @{b}Unsent mail@{ub}                envelope without postage stamp
 @{b}Sent mail@{ub}                  envelope with postage stamp
 @{b}Mail with sending error@{ub}    torn envelope
 @{b}Mail marked for deletion@{ub}   small trashcan

 The second column contains, depending on the folder, either the sender or
 the receiver of the message. If a message has more than one recipient, a
 small symbol (three faces) is put before that name. The third column
 contains the subject, the fourth column the date and the last column
 shows the size of the message in kbytes.
 A double click on a entry in the list opens the @{"read window" link "NdRE"} and shows the
 contents of the mail.


 @{b}@{i}FUNCTIONS @{ui}@{ub}

 Different actions can be started with the three rows of buttons. Normally
 they affect only the active message. Buttons marked with * will perform
 the action on all selected messages. You can select multiple messages by
 holding down the shift key.

 @{b}[Read]@{ub}
 Loads the message into the @{"read window" link "NdRE"}.

 @{b}[Forward]@{ub}
 Redirects a letter to another receiver. Subject and message text are
 automatically taken over.

 @{b}[Delete]@{ub} *
 Deletes one or more messages. If the option "Delete messages on exit"
 is enabled, the message is being marked as deleted, otherwise it is
 removed immediately.

 @{b}[Get address]@{ub}
 The address of the sender (or recipient, depending on the active folder)
 of the active message is filed in your @{"address book" link "NdAB"}.

 @{b}[Write]@{ub}
 Opens the @{"write window" link "NdWR"} where you compose a new message.

 @{b}[Undelete]@{ub} *
 Resets the status of a message marked for deletion.

 @{b}[Get mail]@{ub}
 Tries to connect to your mail server, checks for new mail and loads
 it into the folder "Incoming".

 @{b}[Reply]@{ub}
 Answers a letter addressed to you. Subject and recipient are
 automatically filled in and the original text is quoted.

 @{b}[Filter]@{ub}
 Applies any user defined filters to all messages in the "Incoming" folder.

 @{b}[Archive]@{ub} *
 The message gets moved from "Incoming" to "Archived" or to any other custom
 archive folder.

 @{b}[Edit]@{ub}
 Gives you the possibility to edit a message which is already queued for
 sending.

 @{b}[Send]@{ub} *
 Builds a connection to your mail server and sends the selected message.

 @{b}[Send all]@{ub}
 Sends all messages in "Outgoing".

 @{b}[Send again]@{ub} *
 Moves already sent messages back to the outgoing folder.

 @{b}[Move]@{ub} *
 The message gets moved from the current folder to a different archive
 folder.


 @{b}@{i}MENUS IN THE MAIN WINDOW @{ui}@{ub}

 @{b}Project/About@{ub}
 Shows @{"Copyright information" link "Copy"}.

 @{b}Project/Hide@{ub}
 Switches the program into the iconified mode. The icon shows the status of
 the incoming mail (empty, old, new). The regular mail check and the
 @{"ARexx-interface" link "Rexx"} stay active.

 @{b}Project/Quit@{ub}
 Ends YAM.

 @{b}Folder/Select all@{ub}
 Selects all messages in the active folder.

 @{b}Folder/Remove deleted@{ub}
 Scans all folders for messages which are marked for deletion and removes
 them immediately.

 @{b}Folder/Update index@{ub}
 Scans the mail directory of the current folder and rebuilds the index
 file.

 @{b}Folder/Import@{ub}
 Lets you import a mailbox file generated by another mail application.
 The file must be in standard mailbox format.

 @{b}Folder/Export@{ub}
 Saves all messages in the active folder in a single text file, so they
 can be read from another mail application.

 @{b}Settings/Address Book@{ub}
 Enables you to edit entries in the @{"address book" link "NdAB"}.

 @{b}Settings/Configuration@{ub}
 Opens the @{"configuration window" link "NdCO"}.

 @{b}Settings/MUI@{ub}
 Starts the @{"MUI" link "MUI"} preferences, and enables you to arrange the graphical
 interface of YAM as desired.

 @{b}ARexx/Execute script@{ub}
 Lets you select an @{"ARexx" link "Rexx"} script and executes it.


 @{b}@{i}KEYBOARD SHORTCUTS IN THE MAIN WINDOW @{ui}@{ub}

 LEFT and RIGHT cursor keys are used to switch from one folder to the
 next.
 DEL does the same thing as the [Delete] button.
@endnode

@node "NdCO" "Configuration"

 @{b}@{i}CONFIGURATION @{ui}@{ub}

 These program options are split into eight sections. The button @{b}[Save]@{ub}
 saves the configuration to disk, so they'll survive a restart of the
 computer. Settings saved with @{b}[Use]@{ub} are stored in memory and get lost
 at the next reset.


 @{b}START@{ub} - necessary details to get YAM working

 @{b}Real name@{ub}
 Your real first name and surname. Make sure this is filled in properly.
 Don't use the quotation mark " in your name.

 @{b}Email address@{ub}
 This is your email address, its format is userid@domain.

 @{b}POP3 server@{ub}
 The Internet address which you use get your mail. This server, usually a
 computer from your internet service provider, must be able to handle the
 POP3 protocol. If you leave this field empty, the SMTP server address
 is used.

 @{b}Password@{ub}
 The password you use to log into the mail server.


 @{b}RECEIVE@{ub} - options used to receive mail

 @{b}POP3 UserID@{ub}
 Enter the user id to connect to the POP3 server if it is different from the
 user id used in your email address.

 @{b}Check for mail every x minutes@{ub}
 YAM will make a connection to your mail server, according to your chosen
 interval, and check for new mail.

 @{b}Get mail on startup@{ub}
 YAM will check for new mail immediately when you start the program. To
 disable this function temporarely start YAM from the Shell with the NOCHECK
 option.

 @{b}Delete mail on server@{ub}
 This option erases all messages on the mail server after reception.

 @{b}Avoid duplicates@{ub}
 This option forces YAM to check the Message-ID of every new message and
 doesn't download it if the ID already exists in the message base.

 @{b}Transfer window@{ub}
 Select "none" to disable the transfer window when receiving or sending
 mail.

 @{b}New mail reporting@{ub}
 Select the type of notification for new mail. Default is "beep/requester",
 which brings up a requester displaying the number of new messages and
 does a DisplayBeep(). If you want to be notified with a sound, select
 "external program" and enter a command like "C:Play AUDIO:Beep.snd".

 @{b}Confirm download@{ub}
 For new messages which are larger than the threshold specified here, a
 requester will pop up and give you the choice of loading, deleting or
 skipping the message. Select "on" to get the requester for every mail or
 "off" to disable this feature.


 @{b}SEND@{ub} - options used to send mail

 @{b}SMTP server@{ub}
 The Internet address which you use to send all your mail. This server,
 usually a computer from your internet provider, must be able to handle the
 SMTP protocol.

 @{b}Reply to@{ub}
 Your default reply address is your email address. If you want to use a
 different address, specify it here.

 @{b}Organization@{ub}
 If you want to see the name of your company, school, club, etc. in the
 header of your mails, enter it here.

 @{b}Send mail on startup@{ub}
 With this option checked, YAM will scan the outgoing folder for waiting
 messages and ask you to send them. To disable this function temporarely
 start YAM from the Shell with the NOCHECK option.


 @{b}FOLDER@{ub} - options concerning mail folders

 @{b}Confirm deletion before x or more messages are selected@{ub}
 If this option is selected, you must confirm a safety check before YAM
 erases a defined number of messages.

 @{b}Delete messages on exit@{ub}
 Select this option to delay the removal of deleted messages until the
 program exits. This will allow you to recover deleted messages with the
 [Undelete] button.

 @{b}Folders@{ub}
 This is a list of the mail folders known by YAM. Four of them (colored
 white) can't be modified, but you can add up to 48 additional archive
 folders to store your messages (colored black). Click on [New] to add
 another folder, use [Delete] to remove it.

 @{b}Name@{ub}
 The name of the custom archive folder.

 @{b}Sort by@{ub}
 Sorts the messages in the selected folder as desired. You can sort by
 date, subject or sender.


 @{b}FILTER@{ub} - user defined mail filters

 The purpose of a filter is to process mail in the incoming folder. If
 a message meets some conditions, it will be moved to an archive folder,
 deleted and/or forwarded to another person. You can specify up to 48
 such filters (also known as rules). Click on [New] to add a new filter,
 use [Delete] to remove it.

 @{b}Apply to new mail@{ub}
 Select this option to automatically apply the filters to all new messages.
 You can do the filtering manually by clicking the "Filter" button.

 @{b}Name@{ub}
 The name of the filter (just a description for you).

 @{b}Match@{ub}
 Enter the string pattern you want to search for. You may use AmigaDOS
 expressions like #? etc.

 @{b}Field@{ub}
 Select the header field you want to check.

 @{b}Enable@{ub}
 If you want to disable a single filter without having to delete it, then
 use this option.

 @{b}Case sensitive@{ub}
 Select this option to do a case sensitive comparison.

 @{b}If not true@{ub}
 Use this option to invert the result of the comparison.

 @{b}Action@{ub}
 The type of action you want to perform on matching messages. Enter an
 email address into the "Forward to" field to send a copy of the message
 to someone else. Simultaneously you can delete the message or store it
 in one of your archive folders.


 @{b}READ@{ub} - options for reading mail

 @{b}Message header@{ub}
 Select "Full" to display the complete message header, "Short" to show the
 To, From, Subject and Date fields only or "None" to skip the header.

 @{b}Read window font@{ub}
 Select a font for the @{"read window" link "NdRE"}. You might prefer a non-proportional
 font to display tables and signatures properly.

 @{b}Decode files to@{ub}
 This is the default place to save attached files.

 @{b}MIME viewers@{ub}
 By default YAM will use MultiView to display attached files. Messages
 in MIME format have got an ContentType field which contains the type of
 the encoded file. You can specify individual viewers program for each
 content type. This is important for WB 2.x users (no datatypes!) and
 graphic card owners. Click on [New] to add another folder, use [Delete]
 to remove it.
 Example: to display pictures in JPEG format, you can add an entry with
 MIME type set to "image/jpeg" and viewer set to "TOOLS:Gfx/ViewJPG %s".

 @{b}MIME type@{ub}
 This the MIME content type for the current entry. You may choose one from
 the pop up list or use AmigaDOS wildchars (e.g. "image/#?").

 @{b}Viewer@{ub}
 Select the program you want to use to display the file. Don't forget to
 insert '%s' in the command line, it will be replaced with the actual
 file name.


 @{b}WRITE@{ub} - options for composing new messages

 @{b}Start replies with@{ub}
 If you reply a message, this text will be appended to the new letter.
 You can use several variables: %n is the full name of the recipient, %f is
 his first name, %e his email address, %d the message date, %w the day of
 the week, %t is the time and %s the subject of the message. Line breaks
 may be inserted using \n.

 @{b}Start forwarded messages with@{ub}
 If you forward a message, this text will be appended to the new letter.
 See above for available variables.

 @{b}Use signature@{ub}
 This option adds your signature to every new message by default. You can
 edit the signature in the text editor by choosing [Edit signature].

 @{b}Quote original mail@{ub}

 This option will quote the received text in the answering message. Each
 line of the quoted message will be appended by the text specified in
 @{b}start with@{ub}, followed by a space. You can use %i to get the
 initials of the original sender.


 @{b}SYSTEM@{ub} - different setups

 @{b}External editor@{ub}
 If you don't want to use the internal editor of YAM, you can choose your
 favorite text editor to @{"write" link "NdWR"} your messages. The default
 editor is the Workbench editor "C:Ed".

 @{b}Directory for tempfiles@{ub}
 YAM will store some work files in this directory. If you're short on
 memory (less than 2 MB), select a place on your hard disk to avoid
 problems with large messages.

 @{b}Icon position@{ub}
 Enter a position for the AppIcon of YAM.

 @{b}Closegadget iconifies program@{ub}
 Normally the closegadget (= Esc key) is used to quit the program. Select
 this option if you want YAM to iconify only.


 @{b}@{i}MENUS IN THE CONFIGURATION WINDOW @{ui}@{ub}

 @{b}Project/Open@{ub}
 Loads the configuration from a file. So you're able to use different sets
 of parameters (e.g. if you have accounts with two providers).

 @{b}Project/Save as@{ub}
 Saves the current configuration with a different name.

 @{b}Edit/Reset to Defaults@{ub}
 Resets all current configurations to the stored default settings in YAM.

 @{b}Edit/Last Saved@{ub}
 Changes the current configuration to the one which was valid while booting.

 @{b}Edit/Restore@{ub}
 Resets all changes since the last [Save] or [Use].


 @{b}@{i}HIDDEN CONFIGURATION SETTINGS @{ui}@{ub}

 There are a few parameters that are not yet settable in the configuration
 window. You have to load the file @{b}YAM:.config@{ub} in an editor and
 modify these parameters manually.

 @{b}EditorFont@{ub}
 This is the font you want to use in the internal editor. If want to do
 some ASCII art, set it to a non-proportional font like topaz/8 or XEN/9.

 @{b}TabSize@{ub}
 The internal editor inserts spaces when you press the TAB key. This
 option allows you to set the number of spaces.

 @{b}WordWrap@{ub}
 Select the maximum line length for your message. YAM will automatically
 split any lines exceeding this length. Set WordWrap to 0 if you want
 to disable this feature.
@endnode

@node "NdAB" "Address book"

 @{b}ADDRESS BOOK@{ub}

 The address book is a directory for frequently used addresses. You can
 rearrange the entries in the list using drag & drop.

 @{b}Open@{ub}
 Opens all branches of the address book tree, so all entries will be
 visible.

 @{b}Close@{ub}
 Closes all branches of the address book tree, so only the root entries
 will be visible.

 @{b}To:@{ub}
 Uses the selected entry as primary recipient for a new message.

 @{b}CC:@{ub}
 Uses the selected entry as secondary recipient for a new message.

 @{b}BCC:@{ub}
 Uses the selected entry as blind copy recipient for a new message.

 @{b}New user@{ub}
 Opens the @{"edit address window" link "NdEA"} to add a single person.

 @{b}New list@{ub}
 Opens the @{"edit address window" link "NdEA"} to add a list to the address book. A list
 is a collection of individual users which are addresses with a single
 alias.

 @{b}New group@{ub}
 Opens the @{"edit address window" link "NdEA"} to add a new group. A group is some
 kind of directory which contains persons, list and other groups.

 @{b}Reload@{ub}
 Loads the address book from the hard disk and rejects all unsaved entries.

 @{b}Edit@{ub}
 You can modify the selected entry in the @{"edit address window" link "NdEA"}.

 @{b}Delete@{ub}
 Deletes the selected entry from the address book.

 @{b}Save@{ub}
 Saves the address book on the hard disk.
@endnode

@node "NdEA" "Edit address"

 @{b}ADDRESS INPUT@{ub}

 A single entry from the @{"address book" link "NdAB"} can be edited in this window.

 @{b}Alias@{ub}
 Name used to identify this entry (e.g. first name, nickname, name of
 the group or list).

 @{b}Description@{ub}
 A text string which describes the current entry.

 @{b}Real Name@{ub}
 First- and surname of the receiver.

 @{b}Email address@{ub}
 Internet address of receiver (i.e. mbeck@access.ch).

 @{b}Members@{ub}
 A list of all members in the current list. You can enter aliases, names
 and complete email addresses. Click on [New] to add a another member to
 the list, use [Delete] to remove it.

 @{b}[Okay]@{ub}
 Accepts changes.

 @{b}[Cancel]@{ub}
 Reject changes.
@endnode

@node "NdWR" "Write"

 @{b}@{i}WRITE MESSAGES@{ui}@{ub}

 This window is used to write, modify, reply and forward messages.
 The large text entry field on the MESSAGE page is used to enter your
 letter. Click @{"here" link "Edit"} for a list of available editing commands. If you
 want to highlight words or sentences, you can use the following textstyles:
    _underlined_    *bold*    /italic/

 @{b}[Editor]@{ub}
 If you don't like the internal editor, you can click this button to
 launch your favorite text editor.

 @{b}[To queue]@{ub}
 Prepares the message for transmission and copies it into the "Outgoing"
 folder. Use this button if you're working in off line mode.

 @{b}[Send now]@{ub}
 Prepares the message for transmission, copies it into the "Outgoing"
 folder and tries to send it to your mail server.

 @{b}[Cancel]@{ub}
 In case you decide differently... All entries in this window will be
 lost.


 @{b}MESSAGE@{ub}

 @{b}To@{ub}
 This field contains the primary recipients of the message you're going
 to write. You can enter aliases or names from the address book or even
 complete email addresses if the recipient doesn't exist in the address
 directory. Multiple recipients have to be separated with commas. To get
 an entry from the address book, proceed as follows:
 Open the address book by clicking the pop up gadget on the right side.
 Select the desired entry and simply drag it over this string gadget or
 click the To: button.

 @{b}Copy to@{ub}
 This recipient listed here get a copy of the new message. See above.

 @{b}Subject@{ub}
 The topic of the message. Answered mail is preceded by "Re:", forwarded
 mail extended with "(fwd)".


 @{b}ATTACHMENTS@{ub}

 You can attach one or more files to your letter. This is a means to
 transmit binary files like archives, pictures e.t.c. through email.
 You can choose the type of encoding (@{"MIME" link "MIME"} or UUencoded) and add a
 description for each file.
 The attachments list contains four columns: file name, size of the file
 in bytes, type of encoding and description. You can rearrange the
 entries the list by drag & drop.

 @{b}[New]@{ub}
 Adds another attachment by selecting a file from the requester. YAM
 recognizes some file types and sets the Content Type accordingly.

 @{b}[Delete]@{ub}
 Removes the selected attachment from the list.

 @{b}[Display]@{ub}
 Displays the selected attachment using a program from the MIME
 viewer list (defaults to MultiView).

 @{b}Encoding@{ub}
 In most cases you should encode your files using @{"MIME" link "MIME"} (base64/qp).
 YAM uses quoted-printable for text files and base64 for binaries.
 If the recipient isn't able to decode messages in MIME format (because
 his mailer doesn't support it), you can UUencode the file. Messages
 containing UUencoded files are still in MIME multipart/mixed format,
 but they can be detached with a UUdecoder like UUxT. A message
 written with YAM can contain both, UUencoded and base64 attachments.

 @{b}Content type@{ub}
 If YAM recognizes the type of the attached file, the correct MIME
 type will be inserted automatically. If it fails, the default
 (application/octet-stream) is used.

 @{b}Description@{ub}
 You may enter a comment for the selected attachment.


 @{b}OPTIONS@{ub}

 @{b}Blind copy to@{ub}
 The recipients listed here get a copy of the message. Unlike
 addresses listed in the Cc: field, addresses listed here do not
 appear in the message header of the recipients.  This is useful
 when you want to send a copy of a message to someone without
 everyone else knowing you did so.

 @{b}Reply to@{ub}
 This option is only valid for the current message and overrides
 the default return address specified in the preferences.


 @{b}@{i}MENUS IN THE WRITE WINDOW @{ui}@{ub}

 @{b}Text/Clear all@{ub}
 Clears the whole text in the editor.

 @{b}Text/Insert file@{ub}
 Lets you insert an ASCII text file at the cursor position.
@endnode

@node "Edit" "Editor commands"

 @{b}Documentation for the internal editor (textfield.gadget)@{ub}

 textfield.gadget is Copyright © 1995 Mark Thomas
 All rights reserved.

 You can mark text for cutting, copying, and erasing by simply clicking
 and dragging.  Hitting alphanumeric keys replaces the text that is
 highlighted.  Hitting cursor keys moves you to the front or end of the
 highlighted text.
 If your cursor is already somewhere in the text field, you can hold the
 SHIFT key and click to mark the text from the current cursor position
 to the place where you clicked.
 And the last way to mark text is to double-click, which will mark the
 word you clicked on.  If you didn't click on a word, but rather you
 clicked on spaces, the whole block of spaces is marked.  And if you
 clicked on word delimiters, the whole block of delimiters is marked.
 While you drag to scroll, the farther away from the gadget your mouse
 pointer is, the faster the gadget will scroll.

 For key sequences, the Amiga Style Guide was followed.

 Key Sequence              Function
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 SHIFT CURSOR UP           Move to the top line in the current page, or
                           scroll up one page if cursor is on top line
 SHIFT CURSOR DOWN         Move to the bottom line in the current page,
                           or scroll down one page if cursor is on top
                           line
 SHIFT CURSOR RIGHT        Move to the right end of the current line
 SHIFT CURSOR LEFT         Move to the left end of the current line
 CTRL CURSOR UP            Move to the top line of the text
 CTRL CURSOR DOWN          Move to the bottom line of the text
 ALT CURSOR RIGHT          Move to the next word
 ALT CURSOR LEFT           Move to the previous word
 ALT CURSOR UP             Move to first character in gadget
 ALT CURSOR DOWN           Move to last character in gadget

 SHIFT BACKSPACE           Delete all text to the left of cursor on the
                           current line
 SHIFT DELETE              Delete all text to the right of the cursor
                           on the current line (in block cursor mode
                           this also includes the highlighted
                           character)
 ALT BACKSPACE             Deletes the word to the left of the cursor
                           starting at the current cursor position
 ALT DEL                   Deletes the word to the right of the cursor
                           starting at the current cursor position
 CTRL X                    Deletes the whole line that the cursor is on

 RAMIGA E                  Erase all text in gadget (saved in undo
                           buffer)
 RAMIGA V                  Paste text from clipboard to current cursor
                           position
 RAMIGA A                  Mark all text
 RAMIGA U                  Undeletes (pastes) the last block of text
                           marked, or recover from RAMIGA E

 When text is highlighted the following keys have functions:

 BACKSPACE                 Erase marked text (saved in undo buffer)
 DEL                       Erase marked text (saved in undo buffer)
 RAMIGA X                  Cut marked text to clipboard
 RAMIGA C                  Copy marked text to clipboard
 RAMIGA V                  Replace marked text with text from
                           clipboard (save marked text in undo
                           buffer)
 (any text key)            Replace marked text with that character
@endnode

@node "NdRE" "Read"

 @{b}READ MESSAGES@{ub}

 If you double click a message in the main window or choose the button
 [Read] the active message will be displayed in the read window.
 Header information, if switched on, and attached files shows in white,
 quotes in bold print.

 @{b}[<]@{ub}
 Displays the message on top of the current message in the mail folder.

 @{b}[>]@{ub}
 Displays the message below the current message in the mail folder.

 @{b}[Previous]@{ub}
 Displays the message which is current in the active message.

 @{b}[Next]@{ub}
 Displays the mail in which the current message is answered. [Previous]
 and [Next] are used to trace a dialog between you and someone else
 independent to all other mail in the mail folders.

 @{b}[Reply]@{ub}
 To answer the current message. Subject and recipient are automatically
 filled in and the original text gets quoted.

 @{b}[Archive]@{ub}
 The current message gets moved from "Incoming" to "Archived" or to
 any other custom archive folder. YAM then automatically loads the
 following message.

 @{b}[Delete]@{ub}
 Deletes the current message. If the option "Delete messages on exit"
 is enabled, the message is being marked as deleted, otherwise it is
 removed immediately. YAM then automatically loads the following
 message.

 @{b}[Save]@{ub}
 Saves the current message or a part of it to disk. You can select the
 original message (in raw format), the textual parts (the portions
 of the message which are displayed in the read window) or one of the
 attached files. Press the ESC key to abort the selection.

 @{b}[Print]@{ub}
 Prints the current message or a part of it to disk. You can select the
 original message (in raw format), the textual parts or one of the
 attached text files (you can't print binary attachments like pictures,
 use the print option of the appropriate MIME viewer to do this).

 @{b}[Display]@{ub}
 Displays the current message or a part of it with one of the configured
 MIME viewers. You can select the original message (for debugging
 reasons) or any of the attached files. If this function fails, check
 the MIME viewer settings in the READ section of the preferences.


 @{b}@{i}MENUS IN THE READ WINDOW @{ui}@{ub}

 @{b}Header@{ub}
 Toggles the header information. This setting will be lost when you quit
 YAM, unlike the option in the @{"configuration window" link "NdCO"}.


 @{b}@{i}KEYBOARD SHORTCUTS IN THE READ WINDOW @{ui}@{ub}

 Use SPACE and BACKSPACE to page through the current message.
 LEFT and RIGHT cursor keys are used to display the previous or next
 message in the mail folder. Hold down the SHIFT key to display only new
 and unread messages.
 DEL does the same thing as the [Delete] button.
@endnode

@node "NdER" "Error Messages"

 @{b}ERROR MESSAGES@{ub}

 Whenever an error occurs, YAM displays the error window. New errors
 will be added to the bottom of the list. Click the [Clear messages]
 button to delete all entries in the list.

 Check the following list if you get an error message and don't know
 why...

 @{b}Can't open library 'x', version y@{ub}
 Check LIBS:, MUI:Libs and SYS:Classes for the named library.
 Maybe you have to get a newer version of MUI.

 @{b}Can't create MUI custom classes@{ub}
 @{b}Can't allocate ASL structure@{ub}
 @{b}Can't open timer.device@{ub}
 You're probably low on memory. Quit other running tasks.

 @{b}Can't create application@{ub}
 You're low on memory or YAM is already running.

 @{b}AmiTCP is NOT running!@{ub}
 Execute the AmiTCP startnet script.

 @{b}Read error on mail file@{ub}
 @{b}Can't find the mail file@{ub}
 Check the directory of the "Outgoing" folder. Select the "Update
 index" menu item.

 @{b}Invalid address 'x'@{ub}
 The SMTP server didn't accept a given recipients address. Check
 for invalid characters.

 @{b}Unknown SMTP server 'x'@{ub}
 Make sure you're on line. Check the spelling of SMTP server entry in
 your configuration.

 @{b}Unknown POP3 server 'x'@{ub}
 Make sure you're on line. Check the spelling of POP3 server entry in
 your configuration.

 @{b}No connection to 'x'@{ub}
 @{b}Can't connect to 'x'@{ub}
 Make sure you're on line and check the spelling of the mail server
 entries in your configuration. Ask your provider if he supports
 the POP3 protocol.

 @{b}Can't create mail directory@{ub}
 Verify the path of the mail root directory. By default, it should be
 YAM:. Also check the MAILDIR tooltype option.

 @{b}Cannot save configuration to 'x'@{ub}
 Verify the path of the mail root directory. Also check the PREFSFILE
 and MAILDIR tooltype options.

 @{b}Unknown MIME encoding: x@{ub}
 @{b}Unknown header encoding: x@{ub}
 YAM can't decode a part of a MIME formatted message. Save the
 message to disk and try a different decoder (Metamail, ZMime).

 @{b}Incomplete multipart message: unexpected end of file@{ub}
 @{b}Can't extract MIME message@{ub}
 @{b}Missing boundary in multipart message@{ub}
 @{b}Unexpected EOF while decoding a BASE64 encoded file@{ub}
 The MIME message is broken or badly formed. Use "Display Original"
 to see the raw message.

 @{b}Can't create mail file@{ub}
 @{b}Can't create temporary file@{ub}
 You're probably out of memory. Redirect the directory for tempfiles
 to your hard disk.

 @{b}Unexpected EOF while decoding a UUencoded file@{ub}
 @{b}Invalid line length in UUencoded file: x@{ub}
 @{b}Decoded size [x] does not match original size [y]@{ub}
 An UUencoded file is corrupt or incomplete. Save the original message
 to disk and try a different UUdecoder.

 @{b}Unknown alias or name: x@{ub}
 The alias or name you entered cannot be found in the address book,
 so YAM isn't able to resolve the email address of the recipient.
 Check the spelling of the alias/name.

 @{b}Ambiguous alias or name: x@{ub}
 An alias must be unique, otherwise YAM can't resolve the address.
 Check your address book for duplicate aliases or names.

 @{b}Mail is incomplete: No recipient!@{ub}
 You forgot to specify the recipient(s) of the letter. Just fill in
 the "To" field.

 @{b}Bad x command response: y@{ub}
 The mail server can't process the command x that YAM sent to it.
 The error is explained in y and depends on your mail server.

 @{b}Write error on mail file: x@{ub}
 YAM can't save the new message to disk, probably because of a "disk
 full" error.
@endnode

@node "Opti" "Startup Options"

 @{b}STARTUP OPTIONS@{ub}

 YAM knows some special startup options, which can be used both from
 the Shell and from the Workbench (as Tooltypes):

 @{b}MAILDIR=path@{ub}
 Sets the root for the YAM directory structure. This allows you
 to keep mail databases for multiple users. Default is YAM:

 @{b}PREFSFILE=filename@{ub}
 This is the configuration file you want to use. If you have several
 mail accounts, then you need different settings.
 Default is <MAILDIR>/.config

 @{b}HIDE@{ub}
 Starts YAM in iconified mode.

 @{b}NOCHECK@{ub}
 Disables "Send mail/Get mail on startup" (for example  if you launch
 YAM within a WWW browser).

 @{b}DEBUG@{ub}
 This option will display any conversation between YAM and the mail
 server in the Shell window.

 @{b}POP3=number@{ub}
 Specify the port of the POP3 service. Default is 110 (standard).

 @{b}SMTP=number@{ub}
 Specify the port of the SMTP service. Default is 25 (standard).
@endnode

@node "Rexx" "ARexx Interface"

 @{b}@{i}AREXX INTERFACE @{ui}@{ub}

 YAM includes an ARexx interface which allows other programs to use
 functions of YAM. The portname of this interface is 'YAM'.


 @{b}COMMAND-REFERENCE@{ub}

 @{b}_____________________Standard commands provided by MUI_________________@{ub}

 @{b}quit@{ub}
 Terminate YAM.

 @{b}hide@{ub}
 Switch YAM into iconified mode.

 @{b}show@{ub}
 Recover from iconified mode.

 @{b}info          ITEM/A@{ub}
 Returns information about YAM in the variable RESULT.
 ITEM is one of the following keywords:
   @{b}TITLE@{ub}       program title
   @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}      author name
   @{b}COPYRIGHT@{ub}   copyright note
   @{b}DESCRIPTION@{ub} short description
   @{b}VERSION@{ub}     program version
   @{b}BASE@{ub}        name of the ARexx port
   @{b}SCREEN@{ub}      name of the public screen

 @{b}help          FILE/A@{ub}
 Write a list of all supported ARexx commands into a file.


 @{b}______________________________Get new mail_____________________________@{ub}

 @{b}mailcheck@{ub}
 Corresponds to the button [Get mail]. RESULT contains the number of new
 messages or -1 if the connection to the mail server has failed.

 @{b}mailfilter    ALL/S@{ub}
 Applies rules to the messages in the incoming folder. If you don't
 specify the ALL switch, only new messages will be filtered. RESULT
 contains the number of checked, forwarded, archived and deleted
 messages, e.g. '12 0 3 0'


 @{b}______________________________Edit messages____________________________@{ub}

 @{b}setfolder     FOLDER/A@{ub}
 Change the active folder. FOLDER must be a valid folder name or a number
 in the range of 0 (Incoming) to 3-51 (archive folders).

 @{b}setmail       NUM/N/A@{ub}
 Set the active message in the active folder. The value of NUM must be
 in the range of 0 to (number of entries-1).

 @{b}getfolderinfo INFO/A@{ub}
 Returns information about the active folder in the variable RESULT.
 INFO is one of the following keywords:
   @{b}NUM(BER)@{ub}  number (0=Incoming, 1=Outgoing, etc.)
   @{b}NAM(E)@{ub}    name of the folder
   @{b}PAT(H)@{ub}    directory path of the folder
   @{b}MAX@{ub}       number of messages

 @{b}getmailinfo   INFO/A@{ub}
 Returns information about the selected message in the variable RESULT.
 INFO is one of the following keywords:
   @{b}ACT(IVE)@{ub}  number (0=first in folder)
   @{b}STA(TUS)@{ub}  status of mail (1 char)
   @{b}FRO(M)@{ub}    sender
   @{b}TO@{ub}        primary receiver
   @{b}REP(LYTO)@{ub} return address
   @{b}SUB(JECT)@{ub} subject
   @{b}FIL(E)@{ub}    full path of mail file

 @{b}mailreply@{ub}
 Same as the button [Reply].

 @{b}mailforward@{ub}
 Same as the button [Forward].

 @{b}mailarchive   FOLDER/A@{ub}
 Same as the button [Archive]. FOLDER must be the name of an archive
 folder name or a number in the range of 3 to 51.

 @{b}maildelete@{ub}
 Same as the button [Delete].


 @{b}______________________Compile and send messages________________________@{ub}

 @{b}mailwrite@{ub}
 Same as the button [Write].

 @{b}writemailto   ADDRESS/A/M@{ub}
 One or more aliases, names or email address to be entered into the To
 gadget in write window.

 @{b}writesubject  TEXT/A@{ub}
 Subject of the message.

 @{b}writeattach   FILENAME/A,DESC,ENCMODE,CTYPE@{ub}
 Adds FILENAME to the attachments list; the optional parameter DESC
 specifies the description, ENCMODE is either MIME or UU and CTYPE
 is the MIME content type for this file.

 @{b}writeletter   FILENAME/A@{ub}
 File with the text for send.

 @{b}writequeue@{ub}
 Same as the button [To queue] in the write window.

 @{b}writesend@{ub}
 Same as the button [Send] in the write window.

 @{b}mailsend@{ub}
 Same as the button [Send] in Outgoing folder.

 @{b}mailsendall@{ub}
 Same as the button [Send all]. RESULT contains the number of sent
 messages or -1 if the connection to the mail server has failed.


 @{b}_____________________________Miscellaneous_____________________________@{ub}

 @{b}getconfiginfo INFO/A@{ub}
 Returns configuration details in the variable RESULT.
 INFO is one of the following keywords:
   @{b}NAM(E)@{ub}    your real name
   @{b}EMA(IL)@{ub}   your email address

 @{b}mailupdate@{ub}
 Same as the menu option "Folder/Update Index".

 @{b}request       BODY/A,GADGETS/A@{ub}
 Creates a requester on the YAM screen and waits for user input. BODY
 is the text displayed in the requester, GADGETS are the labels of
 one or more buttons, separated by |. RESULT contains the code of the
 selected button (1,2,...,0).
 Example:  request 'Do you want to quit?' 'Yes|Don't know|No'



 @{b}AREXX EXAMPLE@{ub}

 The following script scans for messages with the subject "YAM Registration"
 and displays their addresses:

 /* register.rexx */
 OPTIONS RESULTS
 ADDRESS YAM
 SetFolder 3                                  /* go to Archive folder  */
 GetFolderInfo MAX; entries = RESULT          /* get number of mail    */
 DO i=0 TO entries-1                          /* scan all mail         */
   SetMail i                                  /* set topical mail      */
   GetMailInfo SUBJECT                        /* ask subject           */
   IF RESULT = 'YAM Registration' THEN DO     /* criteria accomplished */
     GetMailInfo FROM                         /* ask for sender and    */
     SAY RESULT                               /* display               */
   END
 END
@endnode

@node "Tips" "Tips & Tricks"

 @{b}TIPS & TRICKS@{ub}


 @{b}Adding ARexx scripts to the ARexx menu@{ub}

 Load the .config file into an editor and append one or more lines like
 the examples below:

 RexxMenu0 = YAM:Rexx/AutoAnswer.yam
 RexxMenu1 = REXX:RemoveOld.yam

 You may define up to 10 menu items. Save the .config file and
 (re)start YAM.


 @{b}Setting the path for a specific mail folder@{ub}

 Load the .config file into an editor and modify the 3rd field of the
 desired folder definition. Example:

 before:     Folder4 = 2;3;archive4;MUI Mailinglist
 afterwards: Folder4 = 2;3;DISK3:mail/MUI;MUI Mailinglist

 Copy the old directory to the new place and start YAM again.


 @{b}Fixing the size and position of a window@{ub}

 Start the MUI preferences (menu item "Settings/MUI"), select the WINDOW
 page and make sure that the third of the small system buttons is
 activated. After saving the settings each window now has an additional
 system gadget in the upper right corner.  Clicking on this gadget will
 save the current window size and position for later use.
@endnode

@node "Tech" "Technical"

 @{b}FILE STRUCTURE@{ub}

 The directory YAM: contains the following files and directories:

 @{b}YAM@{ub}              The executable.
 @{b}YAM.info@{ub}         The program icon.
 @{b}YAM.guide@{ub}        This AmigaGuide documentation.

 @{b}Icons/@{ub}           This directory contains three icons which show the status
                  of the incoming mail folder:
                  @{b}empty.info@{ub}  the mail folder is empty
                  @{b}old.info@{ub}    it contains only "old" mail
                  @{b}new.info@{ub}    it contains at least one new mail

 @{b}Rexx/@{ub}            ARexx programs for YAM.

 @{b}.config@{ub}          The configuration file.
 @{b}.addressbook@{ub}     The address book.
 @{b}.signature@{ub}       Your personal signature.

 @{b}incoming/@{ub}        The folder "Incoming".
 @{b}outgoing/@{ub}        The folder "Outgoing".
 @{b}sent/@{ub}            The folder "Sent".
 @{b}archived/@{ub}        The folder "Archived".
 @{b}archiveX/@{ub}        The custom archive folders (X is a number).
                  Each message is a file of its own, The file name is put
                  together from the daynumber since the 1.1.1978 and an
                  increasing number for the current day. The status of
                  the mail is saved in the file comment.
                  Each folder directory contains a file called .index
                  which contains the header information for each message
                  in the folder.
@endnode

@node "Mail" "Mail Transport"

 @{b}MAIL TRANSPORT@{ub}

 YAM uses Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) to transfer your
 outgoing mail to your SMTP server machine, which in turn uses SMTP to
 send your mail to the world at large. Mail from the world at large
 arrives on your Post Office Protocol (POP) server, where it waits for
 YAM to pick it up with Post Office Protocol, version 3 (POP3). The
 mail YAM sends and receives is constructed in accordance with RFC 822
 and RFC 1521 (MIME).


 @{b}Outgoing mail@{ub}

 When you send an e-mail message to someone, YAM uses SMTP to send the
 mail to your local SMTP server computer. That computer then sends the
 mail to your addressee’s computer, also (usually) by means of the SMTP
 protocol.
 Why doesn’t YAM talk directly to your addressee’s computer? For one
 thing, it would take a lot longer for your mail to leave your PC,
 because your PC would have to call up each addressee’s computer and
 deliver your mail. For another, some computers are hard to find; it’s
 much better to let another computer hunt for your addressee than to
 make your Amiga do it. Finally, sometimes your addressee’s computers
 won’t be available when you want to send mail. The SMTP server handles
 this by holding your mail until the other computer is ready to accept
 it, eliminating the inconvenience of having unsent messages hanging
 around on your Amiga.

 @{b}Incoming mail@{ub}

 When somebody sends you mail, other computers use the SMTP protocol to
 deliver the mail to your POP server. Your POP server puts mail in your
 mail drop, where it stays until YAM picks it up. When you check your
 mail, YAM uses POP3 to download your mail to your Amiga.
 Why doesn’t YAM use SMTP to receive your mail? SMTP works best when
 the computers it knows about are always ready for mail. Unless you
 wanted to run YAM and your Amiga 24 hours per day, seven days a week,
 SMTP wouldn’t work very well for you.

@endnode

@node "MIME" "What's MIME?"

 @{b}WHAT'S MIME?@{ub}

 MIME stands for Multipurpose Internet Mail Extensions. MIME serves
 two major purposes: it allows mail applications to tell one another
 what sort of data is in mail, and it also provides standard ways
 for mail applications to encode data so that it can be sent through
 the Internet mail system.


 @{b}MIME Encoding@{ub}

 The Internet uses the SMTP protocol to move mail around.  SMTP is
 limited to the US-ASCII character set. This is a problem for people
 who speak languages other than American English and so need
 accented characters or non-American letters, or for people who want
 to use special symbols like the bullet.

 MIME provides a way around this restriction. It offers two encodings,
 "quoted-printable" and "base64". These encodings use US-ASCII
 character codes to represent any sort of data you like, including
 special characters or even non-text data.
 Quoted-printable is used for data that is mostly text, but has special
 characters for very long lines.  Quoted-printable looks just like
 regular text, except when a special character is used.  The special
 character is replaced with an = and two more characters that represent
 the character code of the special character. So, a bullet in quoted-
 printable looks like =95. No line in quoted-printable is allowed to be
 more than 76 characters long. If your mail has a line longer than 76
 characters, the quoted-printable encoding will break your line in two,
 and put an = at the end of the first line, to signal to the mail
 reader at the other end that the two lines are really supposed to be
 one.
 Base64 encoding is another way to protect binary data from the SMTP
 mail system.  However, Base64 makes no attempt to be legible, and is
 most appropriate for non-text data.


 @{b}MIME Labelling@{ub}

 The other important part of MIME is that it lets mailers communicate
 what kind of data is in a message (or part of a message). The primary
 mechanism used for this is the Content-Type header. The major content
 types are:
   text        legible text
   image       pictures and graphics
   audio       sound
   video       moving pictures
   message     messages or pieces of messages
   multipart   several different kinds of data in a single message

@endnode

@node "Plan" "The Future"

 @{b}THE FUTURE OF YAM @{ub}

 Some features which I'll probably implement in one of the
 next releases:

 - PGP support
 - Support of AS225 TCP/IP stack
 - Full text search
 - Better ARexx interface (extended command set, hooks)
 - Log files
 - NO newsgroups ;-)
@endnode

